				<p><strong>The last thing we wanted you to do was pair our tea blends with a book. The first one is our Aurangzeb blend.</strong></p>
				<p>Well obviously Audrey Truschke's <a href="https://www.amazon.in/Aurangzeb-Life-Legacy-Indias-Controversial/dp/1503602575" target="_blank">Aurangzeb: The Life and Legacy of India's Most Controversial King</a>. Although my favourite thing about Aurangzeb is not a book, but a fascinating article by a friend of mine called Katherine Butler Schofield on <a href=" https://www.jstor.org/stable/4132345?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents" target="_blank">"Did Aurangzeb ban music?"</a>.</p>
				<p><strong>Jaipur blend?</strong></p>
				<p><a href="https://www.amazon.in/Princess-Remembers-Maharani-Gayatri/dp/8171673074" target="_blank">A Princess Remembers: The Memoirs of the Maharani of Jaipur</a> would be an obvious choice. Or <a href="https://www.amazon.in/Jaipur-Nama-Giles-Tillotson/dp/0144001004/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1512984799&sr=1-1&keywords=Jaipur+Nama" target="_blank">Jaipur Nama</a>.</p>
				<p><strong>Kashmiri Kawa?</strong></p>
				<p>The best memoir of Kashmir of the Kashmir conflict - <a href="https://www.amazon.in/Curfewed-Night-Basharat-Peer/dp/8184000901/ref=tmm_pap_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=" target="_blank">Curfewed Night</a>. For anyone who says "Oh the bloody Muslims making trouble again" - If you want to understand why they are making trouble, read Basharat's book.</p>
				<p><strong>Varanasi Blend?</strong></p>
